                                   </list>
            </div>
            <div type="history" n="locations">
                <head>Locations</head>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Found</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="found">set against the west wall of the enclosure, known as 'Senan's Bed', where it was used as the seat of a bench-like structure  
                            in the townland of
                                <placeName type="townland">Scattery Island</placeName> and barony of
                            <placeName type="barony">Moyarta</placeName>. (GPS coordinates
                            <geo>-9.517780, 52.615507</geo>)</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Original</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="origLocation">Find location probably original site</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Last Recorded</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="lastLocation">The ogham stone is currently on display inside the refurbished exhibition centre on Scattery Island. <ref
                                target="http://webgis.archaeology.ie/HistoricEnvironment/?SMRS=CL067-024016-"
                                >National Monuments Service Historic Environment viewer on
                            www.archaeology.ie</ref>. (GPS coordinates
                            <geo>-9.514446, 52.614625</geo>)</rs> 
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="history" n="record">
                <head>History of Recording</head>
                <p><ref type="bibliog" target="#OKA2001"><bibl><author>Okasha and Forsyth</author> 
                    (<date when="2001">2001</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                        >112</biblScope></bibl></ref>) state that this stone was first noted by <ref type="bibliog" target="#WES1897"><bibl><author>Westropp</author> 
                            (<date when="1897">1897</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >285</biblScope></bibl></ref>) as having 'ogham-like' scores, 
                    but that it was overlooked by Macalister and later scholars. </p>
            </div>
